<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow follows overseas shares
lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
FRESH weakness on overseas markets brought further pressure to bear on US
share prices yesterday, which extended their recent sharp fall as investors
worried about the effect on equities of today's expiration of derivatives
contracts, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 13.64 lower at 3,274.12.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 slipped 1.30 to 400.96, while
the American SE composite finished 2.25 down at 377.49 and the Nasdaq
composite 4.07 off at 549.17. Turnover on the New York SE came to 225.6m
shares.
After opening lower following the big declines in Tokyo and London, the
market found little comfort in the day's economic news. The April US trade
deficit of Dollars 7bn was wider than expected, while the decline in weekly
jobless claims was smaller than forecast and indicative of a weak labour
market.
One feature was investor wariness about buying ahead of today's expiration
of futures and options contracts. With the market in its current vulnerable
state, there was concern that the expirations, always a potentially
disruptive force on underlying equity prices, could send shares into a
prolonged tail-spin.
Among individual stocks, Advanced Micro Devices plunged Dollars 5 1/2 to
Dollars 9 in turnover of 8.3m shares after a federal jury ruled that the
company cannot use a piece of Intel software in its clones of Intel
microprocessors. The news lifted Intel Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 51 in
turnover of 8m shares.
IBM rose Dollars 2 to Dollars 94 5/8 after an earnings upgrade from broking
house Merrill Lynch, which raised its 1992 and 1993 profits estimates for
the computer group to Dollars 7.25 and Dollars 9 a share respectively. IBM's
rise gave an initial lift to other big computer stocks, but afternoon
selling erased the gains. Hewlett-Packard finished unchanged at Dollars 65
1/4 , Digital Equipment was off Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 36 1/8 and Compaq
lost a net Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 23 5/8 . Apple, which similar to Intel
is quoted on the Nasdaq market, fell Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 45 1/4 .
Ashland Oil declined Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 27 3/8 after the company said
it expected third-quarter net income to be well below the Dollars 1.19 a
share earned a year ago. On the Nasdaq market, J &amp; J Snack Foods plummeted
Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 9 after warning that third-quarter earnings will be
below the 20 cents a share produced a year earlier.
Canada
TORONTO posted a modest decline in moderate trading after Wednesday's sharp
fall. The composite index ended 11 points weaker at 3,357.2, while losing
issues outnumbered advances by 288 to 235 after volume of 26.5m shares
valued at CDollars 308.4m.
Air Canada, up 25 cents at CDollars 4.95, said passenger traffic increased
by 15.9 per cent in May from a year earlier. The company also announced that
it intends to sell five freighter aircraft.
</TEXT>
