<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / International Company News: Du Pont oil arm in Russian joint
venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONOCO, the energy subsidiary of the Du Pont chemicals group, has agreed to
a joint venture with the Russian government that could involve total
investment of as much as Dollars 3bn.
Conoco claimed last night the deal would mark the first time a US company
had become involved in the development from scratch of a Russian oil field.
First production is not planned until late in 1994.
Conoco said the 50-50 venture, between Arkhangelskgeologia of Russia and
Conoco Timan-Pechora Limited, would be named Polar Lights.
The area to be developed is in the northern Timan-Pechora basin, west of the
Ural mountains and near the Arctic Circle. Recoverable reserves in the first
field set for development are estimated to amount to about 110m barrels.
Conoco claimed the Polar Lights project differed from previous US-Russian
oil projects in that there was no current production in the area and the
entire infrastructure needed to be designed and built from scratch.
