<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / International Company News: Plans for Canary Wharf to be
revealed next week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE administrators of Canary Wharf are expected to present their initial
proposals next Wednesday on the future of the Pounds 1.5bn (USDollars
2.77bn) project in London's Docklands.
According to papers filed by Olympia &amp; York with an Ontario court yesterday,
the Ernst &amp; Young partners who were appointed administrators in late May,
are to submit 'their initial findings and suggested strategy' at a meeting
with Canary Wharf's construction lenders in Toronto.
O&amp;Y also outlined a new debt-restructuring proposal which would include
extending repayments on most of its debt for five years, and the disposal of
some Canadian properties and other investments.
The company reaffirmed an earlier plan to convert some of its CDollars
13.5bn (USDollars 11.2bn) debt into equity, but it continues to insist that
control remain with its existing owners, Toronto's Reichmann family.
The court separately approved an application by a group of Canadian banks to
terminate 13 interest-rate swaps with O&amp;Y. The banks argued that the value
of the swaps, considered an asset, was declining as interest rates fell. The
move freezes the amount of the banks' claim against O&amp;Y in respect of the
swaps.
In its submission, O&amp;Y reiterated the importance of remaining a going
concern. It warned that immediate liquidation would result in 'significant
losses to virtually all groups of creditors'. It also said common management
of its properties 'serves to increase asset values in the aggregate'.
The latest restructuring proposals call for loans to be categorised as
convertible or non-convertible debt. At the end of the five-year standstill
period, convertible debtholders would have the option of exchanging their
claims into common shares,
The company also promised to draw up annual 12-month and 24-month business
plans to be approved by an operating committee representing the creditors.
It proposed liquidating marketable securities on an orderly basis, except
for certain core holdings, including its stakes in Gulf Canada Resources,
newsprint maker Abitibi-Price, and property developer Trizec.
O&amp;Y said yesterday it was selling its 50 per cent stake in a 12-storey
office building under construction in Budapest as the head office of
Hungarian Credit Bank. O&amp;Y expects to remain as manager of the project, but
the buyer, Budapest Financial Centre, will take over its obligation to
invest CDollars 12.5m in the project.
Meanwhile, O&amp;Y's information officer filed his first monthly report on the
ailing developer's financial condition yesterday and promised monthly
briefings to the company's far-flung creditors.
The reports stem from creditors' efforts to obtain more detailed information
since O&amp;Y filed for bankruptcy protection for its Canadian assets on May 14.
O&amp;Y handed control of the Canary Wharf project in London's Docklands to
administrators two weeks later, but its US buildings remain outside the
court orders.
The court order covers about two-thirds of O&amp;Y's CDollars 13.5bn debt.
</TEXT>
