<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Intel wins round in battle with AMD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL, the leading US manufacturer of microprocessor chips for personal
computers, has won a critical lawsuit in its battle to prevent Advanced
Micro Devices from cloning its products. A Californian jury has returned a
verdict that AMD does not, as it has claimed, have the right to use Intel's
microcode, the internal instructions that control a microprocessor.
AMD has won an estimated 30 per cent share of the market for 386
microprocessors, since the company launched its own version of the Intel
device last year.
AMD's stock price fell Dollars 5 1/2 yesterday to close at Dollars 9 while
Intel finished up Dollars 3 1/4 at Dollars 51.
The lawsuit is one of several between the two companies involving AMD's
rights to Intel technology.
The latest decision is a setback to AMD's efforts to become a major
competitor in the microprocessor market.
The latest case involved Intel's 287 math co-processor, a device that works
alongside a microprocessor to boost its calculating speed. Intel had filed
suit against AMD in 1990, charging the company with copyright infringement.
AMD claimed to have a licence to use Intel's microcode under a 1976 pact
between the companies and arguments in the case revolved around
interpretation of the agreement.
Intel said the microcode licence was limited to its use in computer systems
designed for software development, and AMD failed to convince the jury that
its licensing rights were broader.
Intel hailed the decision as a victory in its legal battles with AMD. 'We
are extremely pleased with today's verdict,' said Mr Thomas Dunlap, Intel
general counsel. Mr WJ Sanders, AMD chairman, told employees: 'We have
suffered a setback - not a defeat.'
For 1991, AMD reported revenues of Dollars 1.2bn and profits of Dollars
145.3m. Intel reported record revenues last year of Dollars 4.78bn and
Dollars 819m in profits.
Siemens withdraws from IBM deal, Page 26
