<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / The Maxwells: MPs find cheer in Bank meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS CAMPAIGNING on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners were encouraged
yesterday that Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the governor of the Bank of
England, would take a more active role in assisting in the recovery of
assets.
Three MPs from the all-party group - Mr Richard Page, Mr Frank Field and Mr
David Shaw - met Mr Leigh-Pemberton to express their concerns about what has
been seen at Westminster as too passive a role adopted by the Bank over the
Maxwell affair.
They came away with the impression that the Bank had been acquiring
information more actively behind the scenes, and that it would be working
closely with the special unit to help the pensioners which has been set up
in the department of social security and is led by Sir John Cuckney.
The MPs were also cheered that while Mr Leigh-Pemberton was very conscious
of the limits of the Bank's legal powers, he recognised also the powerful
influence that it could exert.
They expressed confidence that once he was sure of the information on which
he could act, he would be ready to do so, in order to contribute to ensuring
that the government's moral pressure on some banks and financial
institutions was effective.
He is to circulate to the MPs a note of the discussion which will set out
the Bank's position, and is ready to meet them in the autumn if that is
still wanted. The MPs had written asking him to talk to the group, but in
the event he may instead give evidence to the all-party social security
committee once that has been re-established.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton seems to have succeeded in softening the severely
critical stance which many among the 100-strong all-party group had taken
towards his approach.
One or two of the group, however, are still unhappy that the Bank will not
take a broader view of its duties and act as a City-wide regulator.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
