<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Waverers 'relieved by result of
election'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENTIAL opinion polling conducted for Labour after its election defeat
showed that even voters who had once planned to vote for the party expressed
'surprise and relief' at the April 9 outcome, Ivo Dawnay writes.
The findings of the surveys, held to sound out sample groups of potential
floating voters, were a key reason that Labour's national executive
committee avoided recriminations over detailed campaign tactics yesterday.
The poll results were outlined by Mr Philip Gould, the head of the
controversial Shadow Communications Agency, at the NEC meeting. They
graphically demonstrated the alarming shallowness of Labour's support among
those it thought were its supporters.
The so-called qualitative opinion surveys do not give statistical data, but
they indicate broad opinion voiced by men and women voters chosen before the
election as potential waverers.
Researchers found a new readiness to cite 'self-interest' as grounds to vote
against Labour among groups of skilled and semi-skilled workers, aged 25 to
50, in Nottingham and Slough. They were all workers who had indicated their
intention to vote Labour or Liberal Democrat.
Opinions expressed showed uncertainty about what interests the Labour party
now represents and the view that a vote for Labour was no longer a
'self-interested working class vote'.
It was stated that voting for Labour was a vote 'for less fortunate people
by more comfortable, conscientious people'.
Among other reasons for opposition to Labour were negative and off-putting
associations voiced about the party. They included perceptions of Labour as
a party tied to the past, the winter of discontent, inflation and economic
failure, heavy industry and the traditional working class.
</TEXT>
