<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Rise in lending points to upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE second successive monthly rise in lending by banks and building
societies has provided further signals of a modest upturn.
Lending by those groups to companies and individuals rose by a seasonally
adjusted Pounds 3bn last month, after a Pounds 5.1bn increase in April, the
Bank of England said yesterday.
The message about increased demand for credit was supported by the British
Bankers' Association, which said that its nine member banks increased
lending by an adjusted Pounds 2.2bn in May, after Pounds 2.6bn in April.
Any hopes about a strong uplift were dampened by other figures for growth in
the money supply, which indicated weak overall demand for goods and
services.
The Bank's figures for so-called M4 sterling lending to the private sector
came after a net repayment of Pounds 394m in March. M4, or broad money, is
private-sector holdings of notes and coins plus bank and building society
deposits.
The figures indicate that much of the extra lending by the association's
constituent commercial banks was to financial companies, rather than
manufacturers. The association said that as most of the increase in the past
two months had been due to seasonal factors, it was 'difficult to point to
where the demand is coming from'.
Unadjusted for seasonal variations, lending to financial groups increased in
May by Pounds 583m, while manufacturers repaid Pounds 200m of debt.
Individuals borrowed Pounds 462m.
Figures for money supply growth indicated only sluggish demand. Narrow
money, or M0, which comprises mostly notes and coins in circulation, rose a
seasonally adjusted 0.1 per cent last month to give a 2.5 per cent increase
for the year. M0 growth in the year to April was 2.3 per cent.
M4 rose by 0.3 per cent last month, bringing the year-on-year growth rate to
5.2 per cent. That is the lowest year-on-year rate since the Bank started
records in 1976. In April, the year-on-year rate was 5.7 per cent.
Mr Nigel Richardson, an economist at SG Warburg Securities, said the figures
were consistent with moving slowly out of recession. 'We may be seeing a
pick-up from the bottom,' he said.
Over the past year, expansion in the money supply as well as in lending
generally has been subdued as consumers and businesses have concentrated on
paying off debts.
</TEXT>
