<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Rembrandt print makes Pounds 159,500: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PRINT by Rembrandt, 'Christ Crucified between Two Thieves', sold for
Pounds 159,500 at Christie's yesterday, at the bottom of its estimate.
Executed in dryprint in 1653, the print is extremely rare: Rembrandt altered
the com-position dramatically in 1660.
It was the top price in an auction of Old Master prints collected in the
late 19th century by an aristocratic German family and only now being
dispersed. The first group to be sold brought in more than Pounds 2m last
December.
All told, there were 77 Rembrandt prints on offer. His 'Woman in the Bath
with a Hat Beside Her' of 1658 sold for Pounds 121,000, almost double its
estimate, and an etching of a shell, the only example of a Rembrandt still
life, went for Pounds 66,000.
The main disappointment was the failure of Durer's 'Knight, Death and the
Devil', engraved in 1513, to find a buyer.
A jeroboam - equal to six bottles - of Chateau Latour 1864 from the cellars
of Hatfield House, the home of the Marquess of Salisbury, sold for Pounds
6,534 at Christie's yesterday to a German collector.
A surviving jeroboam from this vintage is certainly unique - the bottle is
wrapped in brown paper to keep out the light and delay oxidisation.
A dozen bottles of the 1961 Latour were within forecast at Pounds 4,235,
while one bottle of the Chateau Lafite 1844 made Pounds 2,178. It was the
property of the late Caria Kaspia, the caviar king, the contents of whose
wine cellar totalled more than Pounds 68,000.
A bottle of Grande Fine Champagne cognac of 1818, bearing the legend
Restauration on the label and obviously produced to celebrate the return of
the French monarchy, sold for Pounds 602 at Sotheby's on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
