<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Call for better interim accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STOCK Exchange should demand that companies' interim accounts are more
extensive and should be reviewed by their auditors, the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales said yesterday.
The consultative document issued by the institute's auditing committee
called for interims, which are issued halfway between financial year-ends,
to contain balance sheets and cashflow information, as well details of the
profit-and-loss account.
The document said the Stock Exchange should require listed companies to
provide additional information and be subject to audit, while the Accounting
Standards Board and the Auditing Practices Board should issue appropriate
technical guidance.
The recommendations echo suggestions for an auditor's review of interims in
the Cadbury committee on the financial aspects of corporate governance,
which reported last month.
It also follows a similar proposal by the institute in February for
preliminary statements - which are often issued to the market several weeks
before the annual report - to be reviewed by a company's auditors.
The committee argues that companies' share prices tend to respond far more
to interim and preliminary announcements - which provide little and
unaudited information - than to the audited accounts.
Mr Graham Ward, a partner at Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm, who is
vice-chairman of the committee, said: 'Half-yearly reports are a major
influence on the market, but there are no accounting rules or audit
requirements to ensure that the market is given reliable information.'
Audit procedures on a half-yearly report should include evaluating a
company's internal controls, ensuring that accounting records are up to
date, and examining the minutes of board and management committee meetings.
Published interim reports. FRAG 19/92. ICAEW, Gloucester House, 399 Silbury
Blvd, Milton Keynes MK9 2HL. Free with stamped addressed envelope.
</TEXT>
