<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Big towns will be forced to privatise buses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLIC-SECTOR bus companies in all Britain's largest towns and cities are to
be privatised under plans being prepared by the Department of Transport.
They include state-owned London Buses; the municipally owned bus companies
in the metropolitan areas of Greater Manchester, Merseyside, South Yorkshire
and Strathclyde; and bus companies in cities including Nottingham, Cardiff,
Southampton, and Hull.
Privatisation of the 35 companies will represent the biggest shake-up of
Britain's bus industry since privatisation of the National Bus Company's 56
component companies between 1986 and 1988. That coincided with deregulation
of the bus industry outside London and paved the way for outbreaks of fierce
competition in some parts of the country, followed by a series of mergers
and takeovers.
The latest plans will be outlined tomorrow by Mr Roger Freeman, minister for
public transport, at a private seminar arranged by Capital Strategies, a
London-based consultancy specialising in employee buy-outs.
Mr Freeman is expected to announce that the government intends to legislate
for compulsory privatisation of London Buses and all 34 municipal bus
companies as soon as possible.
The powers will be sought in the same bill as the one planned for the
deregulation of London bus services, for which parliamentary time has not
yet been found.
The government believes most local authorities can be persuaded to privatise
their companies voluntarily. Councils will be told that if they negotiate
deals in advance of legislation, they may be allowed to sell companies to
management-employee buy-out teams without the need for competitive
tendering.
Many local authorities, particularly Labour-led ones, are reluctant to part
with their bus companies. Faced with a choice between a voluntary sale to
the company's employees now or a compulsory sale after legislation, however,
many may choose the former.
Although it is already open to all local authorities to privatise their bus
companies, only nine have chosen to do so. The largest and most recent
example was West Midlands Travel, the former West Midlands Passenger
Transport Executive.
Mr Brian Souter, chief executive of Stagecoach, an acquisitive private bus
company, said he welcomed any move to bring more bus companies into the
private sector. 'But I would be very disappointed if there was not open
market bidding,'he said.
</TEXT>
