<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Head of Guinness family dies at 55
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD Iveagh, head of the Guinness brewing family, died in London yesterday
aged 55 after a short illness.
His death came three weeks after he left the Guinness board - leaving it for
the first time without a descendant of Mr Arthur Guinness, who founded the
Dublin stout brewery in 1759.
He was chairman of the company from 1962 until 1986 when he was succeeded by
Mr Ernest Saunders, later jailed for his part in the takeover of the
Distillers drinks group. Lord Iveagh then became company president until
last month, when he decided not to seek re-election to his position or to
the board.
Last night night Sir Anthony Tennant, Guinness chairman, said: 'I am very
sad to have lost a valued friend and colleague, who gave Guinness tremendous
service over very many years.'
Lord Iveagh, known to his friends as Ben, had joined the board in 1958 as
Viscount Elveden.
The following year he became assistant managing director in charge of the
Park Royal brewery in London. From 1960 his responsibility - still as
assistant managing director - included Dublin as well as London.
He succeeded to the Iveagh title, created in 1919, when his grandfather, the
second earl, died in 1967. His father, then Viscount Elveden, was killed in
action in 1945.
The earldom passes to his elder son Viscount Elveden, 22. He leaves another
son, Rory, 17, and two daughters, Lady Emma, 18, and Lady Louisa, 15.
</TEXT>
