<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Big TV networks can own cable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Federal Communications Commission yesterday announced that it would
allow the three traditional US television networks - NBC, CBS and ABC - to
own cable TV systems, subject to conditions. This ends a 22-year ban.
The agency prohibited cross-ownership of cable and broadcast networks in
1970, when the networks dominated home viewing and the FCC feared they would
trample on the fledgling cable industry.
Since then, however, the networks have suffered a sharp decline in their
share of the national audience as viewers have switched to cable.
The FCC first raised the possibility of relaxing the ban in 1982, but met
strong political opposition. It revived the idea last December.
The new ruling includes safeguards to allay the fears of local broadcasting
stations, not owned by the networks, which fear financially ruinous
competition. The networks would not be permitted to own cable systems
serving more than 10 per cent of homes nationally and 50 per cent of homes
in a local market served by only one cable company.
</TEXT>
