<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / World Trade News: EC ministers water down procurement row
clause
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC MINISTERS have watered down a third-country retaliation clause in new
public procurement legislation which could have aggravated trade friction
with the US, Andrew Hill reports from Luxembourg. Internal market ministers
yesterday agreed a directive which will force utilities to put big service
contracts, ranging from maintenance and cleaning to accountancy and
insurance, to open tender.
The directive is the last in a series designed to liberalise EC public
procurement from the beginning of next year. The US is threatening trade
sanctions over an earlier directive on utility equipment contracts. That
includes a clause allowing utilities to favour EC bids over those from third
countries which have failed to open their own markets to competition.
The US says this so-called 'reciprocity' clause discriminates against non-EC
suppliers, particularly in the telecoms sector, and should be changed before
it comes into force on January 1, 1993.
EC ministers have agreed a more relaxed regime for the services directive.
This will let the Commission investigate alleged discrimination against EC
companies by third countries. Any retaliatory measures will have to be
approved by member states. The new measure will apply to energy, water,
telecommunications and transport companies, publicly or privately owned.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
