<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Commodity price revival
forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Commodities Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICES FOR most commodities could show a strong revival in 1993 if the
economies of the leading industrialised countries recover enough to
stimulate demand for raw materials, according to the Economist Intelligence
Unit, writes Our Commodities Staff.
'We expect the global economy to pick up in 1992 and most commodities are
sensitive to change on the demand side,' said Mr Alec Gordon, editor of the
unit's World Commodity Forecasts.
In the latest edition, of the 26 commodities prices covered by the EIU, 18
are seen as fetching higher prices in 1993 than this year, when many
commodity prices hit new lows because of the recession.
In the soft commodities, crops may be badly hit by drought and the ensuing
supply problems should support prices, Mr Gordon said.
He expected tea, sunflower and soyabean oils prices to do better in 1993
than this year. The coffee and cocoa markets are still heavily oversupplied
but if stock control measures succeed, prices could recover strongly, Mr
Gordon said.
Nickel, with its fortunes strongly linked to stainless steel production,
would benefit from a strengthening consumer goods sector, while use of
copper strongly depended on an upturn in the construction and power
transmission sectors, the EIU said.
