<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Shanks &amp; McEwan pleases City with 30% rise
to Pounds 31.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHANKS &amp; MCEWAN, the waste management company, yesterday reported a 30 per
cent increase in profits, after a full year's contribution from Rechem, the
hazardous waste company it acquired last year.
The final months of the year were, however, severely hit by recession with
volumes of the highest margin wastes particularly affected.
The jump in pre-tax profits from Pounds 23.9m to Pounds 31.1m on sales 24
per cent higher at Pounds 145.8m nevertheless pleased the market, which had
been anticipating a poorer performance, and the shares rose 9p to 207p.
Earnings per share fell from 13.2p to 11.9p and the the final dividend is
maintained at 3.44p, giving a total of 5.7p, up 3.6 per cent on the year.
Mr Peter Runciman, chairman, said that while profit margins had been eroded
the longer-term prospects were 'extremely encouraging.'
Total tonnage handled in the waste division rose by 2 per cent but margins
were eroded and its profits contribution fell from Pounds 12.65m to Pounds
12.55m.
The environmental services division, which includes Rechem, increased
tonnage handled by 13 per cent but processing cost rises were not fully
recovered and profits rose only 10 per cent to Pounds 9.54m.
The technical services, or waste treatment division, increased sales by 18
per cent but profits were only marginally up at Pounds 3.59m.
The construction division increased its contribution from Pounds 1.72m to
Pounds 2.67m.
There was also a Pounds 3.8m one off increase in debt from the Inland
Revenue's request for corporation tax payments to be accelerated.
COMMENT
Shanks &amp; McEwan used to be seen as the Rolls-Royce of a racy industry with
equally racy ratings. Then last year the sector lost some of its glister,
not because its green credentials faded, but because the markets belatedly
realised waste volumes and profits were not recession proof. Nevertheless,
longer term Shanks is a company that will reap the benefit of increasingly
stringent environmental legislation. While the waste treatment division
could still do with some bolstering, its landfill sites have relatively
exclusive market positions and the Rechem acquisition has brought a vital
presence in hazardous waste. But growth will only resume rapidly once the
economy begins to move again. Shanks's costs are largely fixed and there is
therefore little prospect of further cost cutting to boost earnings
dramatically this year. Pre-tax profits are forecast not much higher than
this year's Pounds 31.1m, giving about 12p of earnings again, and puts
Shanks, in the absence of recovery, on a correctly priced 17.3 multiple.
</TEXT>
