<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / ICI warns that signs of rise in UK demand have petered out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries, the British chemicals giant, yesterday warned
analysts that signs of an upturn in UK demand during late March and early
April had petered out.
Mr Ronnie Hampel, chief operating officer, told analysts during a seminar
that the company's caution during the first quarter about prospects for the
rest of the year had been justified.
ICI's shares closed down 36p at Pounds 12.35.
The good few weeks at the end of March and beginning of April had proved to
be restocking. There had been no sign of an upturn in April and May, said Mr
Hampel.
The results of industrial chemical operations were likely to be lower than
last year, he warned.
Only in the US had there been signs of an upturn and even there it had been
weak.
'Any improvements will be the result of self-help,' he said.
'We can only hope rather than expect an economic upturn to help us in the
second half of the year.' He said that, by the end of the second quarter,
restructuring had led to annualised savings of Pounds 250m.
Analysts yesterday downgraded their forecasts explaining that ICI's first
half was always stronger than the second.
Previous estimates of full-year profits had ranged from about Pounds 900m to
Pounds 930m.
After downgrading they were between Pounds 830m and Pounds 875m.
Some analysts were also preparing downgrades for other bulk chemicals
groups.
Agrochemicals had also proved disappointing, said Mr Hampel. Wet, cold
weather in Europe and the US mid-west had meant second-quarter results would
be lower than last year.
Concerns in France about the EC's Common Agricultural Policy reforms had led
to slower sales.
Credit in eastern Europe was also proving a problem.
Analysts, who had expected up to 10 per cent growth from agrochemicals,
believe the division could make less this year than 1991.
</TEXT>
