<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Yorkshire and Tyne Tees agree TV merger: Deal to create
third-largest independent TV company seen as forerunner to industry
consolidation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YORKSHIRE Television and Tyne Tees Television, two northern England
companies that won independent television franchises last year, yesterday
announced terms of a merger.
A recommended offer from Yorkshire values the Tyne Tees share capital at
Pounds 30.4m and the deal has been approved in principle by the Independent
Television Commission.
Such mergers were not expected until after the ITC's formal moratorium on
non-recommended bids was lifted in January 1994. But yesterday's deal is
seen as a forerunner of the consolidation likely to occur among the
companies that won franchises last year.
At Westminster, Mr Robert Maclennan, Liberal Democrat home affairs
spokesman, urged the government to review the Broadcasting Act with a view
to tightening ownership rules. 'When the Broadcasting Act went through
parliament, the then minister in charge, David Mellor, argued strongly
against a regional ITV company taking over a neighbouring TV company,' he
said.
He predicted the merger would 'destabilise' ITV 'as larger groups are formed
to compete effectively for advertising'.
Yorkshire and Tyne Tees were among the highest bidders for franchises last
year and put their finances under some strain, analysts say.
The merger would make the combined group the third-largest independent
television company behind Thames and Central.
The all-share offer involves 17 new Yorkshire shares for every 10 Tyne Tees
shares, valuing each at 292p. Yorkshire last year bought a 20 per cent stake
in Tyne Tees. Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, owns 20 per cent of
Yorkshire.
Yorkshire shareholders will be entitled to a bonus issue of warrants
allowing them to subscribe to Yorkshire shares which, if fully taken up,
would raise Pounds 20m for the combined company.
Mr Clive Leach, Yorkshire chief executive, said the combined group would
have 16 per cent of the ITV audience but 12 per cent of its advertising
revenues.
'Yorkshire's position is undoubtedly relatively improved and it goes some
way to redress the imbalance with companies that got their franchises on
comparatively cheaper terms,' one analyst said.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
