<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / Shorts to cut another 400 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHORT BROTHERS, the Belfast aircraft and missiles manufacturer, announced
400 job losses yesterday.
The company blamed the redundancies on the recession and said they would
affect all areas of its operations.
Shorts, acquired by Bombardier, the Canadian transportation group, in
October 1989, has given 90 days' notice to the Department of Economic
Development.
The company has ceased production of the FD360 commuter aircraft and is
running down production of the 323 Sherpa military aircraft for the US Army
and National Guard.
Shorts said there would be some enforced redundancies but efforts would be
made to keep them to a minimum.
The company added: 'Basically, the reduction has been recession-driven.
'Some of our biggest customers, such as Rolls-Royce, British Aerospace and
Boeing, have been scaling down operations, so there has been a knock-on
effect.'
The job losses come on top of 300 redundancies announced in January, but
overall employment at Shorts is still ahead of the level at the time of its
privatisation.
The company is Northern Ireland's largest private employer with 8,200 in the
province and a further 600 in mainland Britain, compared with a total of
7,500 at the time of the sell-off.
Shorts has doubled turnover in the past 2 1/2 years to about Pounds 400m a
year.
The previously loss-making operation recorded a profit of Pounds 26m in
1990-91.
</TEXT>
