<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUN 92 / EOC warns of pensions 'debacle'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is in danger of creating 'another poll tax debacle' over its
handling of the equalisation of state pension ages for men and women, the
Equal Opportunities Commission warned yesterday.
Many people would not know until it was too late that they might be
substantially worse off under pension measures being considered by the
government, the commission said. Women in particular stood to lose if their
age of entitlement to state pension was raised from 60 to 65 - the present
retirement age for men.
The commission accused the government of failing to consult widely enough
and of blocking some options for reform with 'a selective wall of
statistics'. A Department of Social Security paper on options was issued at
the end of last year. Organisations are to make their comments by the end of
this month.
Moves to equalisation follow a European Court ruling in 1990 that different
retirement ages for men and women are discriminatory. The DSS consultation
paper favoured a common retirement age of 63, while the pensions industry
and organisations such as the British Institute of Management want a
flexible scheme, with retirement possible between 60 and 70.
Ms June Bridgeman, commission deputy chairwoman, said the government was on
the verge of a decision that would shape the pensions system for the 21st
century.
'It will affect many things besides the immediate question of setting a
common age for old-age pensions,' she said. It concerned everyone, yet most
people were unaware that the consultation was taking place.
'It is crucial that the changes make people generally better - not worse -
off and win popular support. If it does not do these things, the government
is in danger of risking another poll tax debacle.'
The commission yesterday described a common pension age of 60 as the 'best
and simplest option'. It said millions of women already had a raw deal and
the commission was concerned that equality might be achieved by making women
even worse off.
She added: 'The largest number of complaints received by the EOC from men is
about pensions. For equality to be achieved to the detriment of women would
be a bitter pill for both sexes.'
A Question of Fairness. Equal Opportunities Commission, Overseas House,
Manchester M3 3HN. Pounds 1.50.
</TEXT>
