<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 92 / London Stock Exchange: Increased selling pressure hits
shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEPRESSING news from the corporate sector, but this time from overseas,
added to the woes of a UK stock market already upset yesterday by a firm
rejection overnight from Mr Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor of the
exchequer, of another early cut in domestic interest rates.
Later, the chancellor followed his strong line on interest rates with a
speech reaffirming the government's commitment to the Maastricht proposals,
in particular to economic convergence and to sterling's entry to the narrow
bands of the ERM range; the market read this as final rejection of political
pressures for an immediate base rates cut.
But it was shock waves from Amsterdam, where Philips warned that
second-quarter profits would be below the comparable period, that finally
upset the UK stock market. Having been 21 Footsie points down in reaction to
Mr Lamont's overnight speech, London was rallying successfully towards
midsession, halving its early fall and regaining the Footsie 2,606 mark,
until the news from Philips threw it into reverse.
Share prices moved lower for the rest of the session and the FT-SE 100 Index
closed 17.9 down at 2,598.4. The market's view of near-term prospects was
fairly gloomy, although most strategists took a cautiously positive view of
the day's list of important economic data.
The rise of 0.3 per cent in retail sales in May was slightly above
expectations, while a 0.2 per cent gain in manufacturing output in April was
regarded as an indication of an uptrend in production.
'Today's economic data are consistent with a slow, steady recovery in the
economy,' said Mr Ian Harnett of Strauss Turnbull, UK securities arm of
Societe Generale. But he drew attention to further data due this week, led
today by wages and unemployment statistics.
The international blue chips were held in check yesterday by firmness in
sterling, which hurts overseas revenues.
On a more domestic level, nervousness was caused again by the prospects of
tomorrow's expiry of the June future on the FT-SE Index. Large positions,
both bullish and bearish, remain open on the June Footsie contract and
prices of the underlying blue chip stocks could be in for heavy and
contrasting pressures as the leading securities houses strive to balance
positions ahead of Friday's futures expiry deadline.
Seaq-reported trading volume remained unimpressive at 423.7m shares, against
391m in the previous session when retail business remained well short of the
Pounds 1bn mark regarded as the sign of a healthy equity market. However,
traders said that 'some stock came out yesterday'.
While not too happy to see the Footsie 2,600 mark so quickly abandoned
again, market professionals held to the view that, while share prices may
remain uncertain for the near future, the relative value of equities against
gilts will provide support. The mildly positive response to yesterday's
economic statistics suggested improved confidence but the Philips statement
turned the spotlight back on to the corporate sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 48
</PAGE>
