   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR LEON Charney, a former adviser to the Carter administration who may
launch a bid for United Press International, said he was considering a plan
to revive the ailing news service through public offerings to subscribers
and correspondents, AP-DJ reports. Under the plan, UPI would become a
co-operative.
Mr Charney, who recently provided Dollars 180,000 to keep UPI operating
until June 22, yesterday met in Amsterdam with a representative of the
National Postal Lottery, which may pump as much as Dollars 3.5m into UPI
under a proposed rescue plan. The foundation raises money through lottery
sales.
The Dutch foundation's efforts are being led by Mr Bob Goldner, an former
UPI executive, and Mr Julian Isherwood, a UPI journalist based in
Copenhagen. It expects a restructured UPI to expand coverage of
environmental and Third World issues.
Mr Charney said an investment by the Dutch foundation, if it materialised,
would provide funds to keep the news wire running for an extended period
while detailed plans for a public offering could be worked out.
